\begin_layout Title
Agreement coefficients with missing raters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
today
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
Department of Data Science and Analytics,
 BI Norwegian Business School,
 Oslo,
 Norway
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Missing data is a pervasive challenge in studies of inter-rater agreement,
 yet common agreement coefficients,
 such as Conger’s kappa,
 Fleiss’ kappa,
 and the Brennan–Prediger coefficient,
 are often applied without clear justification when ratings are incomplete.
 We develop a general framework for handling missing data in agreement analysis that supports both categorical and continuous responses,
 allows arbitrary disagreement functions,
 and hold provided the data is pairwise missing completely at random.
 Then we characterize when pairwise-available estimators remain consistent,
 derive their correct standard errors,
 and identify settings where conventional formulas fail.
 We then propose reweighted kappa estimators that remain valid under substantially weaker assumptions.
 Asymptotic covariance matrices enable joint inference across coefficients,
 and simulations verify the theoretical claims.
 The methods are implemented in an R package 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{misskappa}$
\end_inset

 designed for applied use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A chance-corrected agreement coefficient is any coefficient on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}=1-\frac{d}{d_{x}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a measure of disagreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{x}$
\end_inset

 a measure of chance disagreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}$
\end_inset

 be a random vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 components.
 The vector contains all rating data,
 including potentially unobserved ratings.
 Define disagreement as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})],\label{eq:population disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric loss function satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The by far most common are the nominal (
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

),
 absolute value (
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

),
 and quadratic (
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=(x-y)^{2}$
\end_inset

) losses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We cover three variants of chance disagreement,
 the Fleiss-type 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Cohen-type 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cohen1968-sb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and Brennan–Prediger-type 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Brennan1981-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
d_{F} & = & R^{-2}\sum_{j,k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:fleiss disagreement}\\
d_{C} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:cohendisagreement}\\
d_{BP} & = & C^{-2}\sum_{a,b}l(a,b),\label{eq:bp disagreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i\cdot}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i'\cdot}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 are independent samples from the same distribution.
 In the case of Brennan–Prediger we must assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}$
\end_inset

 takes on 
\begin_inset Formula $C<\infty$
\end_inset

 categorical values.
 Interpretations of these chance disagreements are well-known and can be found elsewhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For complete data,
 the kappa coefficients are estimated using the natural sample counterparts.
 Their standard errors may be found using either multinomial theory or 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moss2024-cc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our task is to estimate and do inference on agreement coefficients in the presence of missing or incomplete data.
 When dealing with incomplete data we do not observe all ratings in
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 We formalize this by defining
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{j}=\begin{cases}
X_{j}^{\star} & M_{j}=1,\\
\text{NA} & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the missingness indicator and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{NA}$
\end_inset

 denotes a missing value.
 We naturally assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 cannot take on the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{NA}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

