We w
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hájek-type inverse probability-weighted estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by describing an inverse probability-weighted estimator of the Hájek-type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the observation probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}=P(M_{j}=1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}=P(M_{j}M_{k}=1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then define the natural sample estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{j}=\hat{P}(M_{j}=1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{jk}=\hat{P}(M_{j}M_{k}=1)$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

 being the empirical probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Hájek-type inverse probability-weighted estimator
\emph default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}=1-\hat{d}^{IPW}/\hat{d}_{C}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

,
 where we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{d}^{IPW} & = & \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})M_{ij}M_{ik}\hat{\pi}_{jk}^{-1}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}\hat{\pi}_{jk}^{-1}},\quad\hat{d}_{C}^{IPW}=\frac{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{i'k})M_{ij}M_{i'k}\hat{\pi}_{j}^{-1}\hat{\pi}_{k}^{-1}}{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{i'k}\hat{\pi}_{j}^{-1}\hat{\pi}_{k}^{-1}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{F}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

being defined analogously to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{C}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

,
 with summation over all 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

.
 This is the natural extension of the Hájek estimator to the agreement setting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from the strong law of large numbers,
 Slutsky's theorem,
 and the continuous mapping theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see, e.g.,"
key "Van_der_Vaart2000-qc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{d}^{IPW} & \stackrel{a.s.}{\to} & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}\pi_{jk}^{-1}E[l(X_{1j},X_{1k})M_{1j}M_{1k}],\quad\hat{d}_{C}^{IPW}\stackrel{a.s.}{\to}\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}\pi_{j}^{-1}\pi_{k}^{-1}E[l(X_{1j},X_{2k})M_{1j}M_{2k}],\label{eq:d_IPW}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

with a similar limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{F}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

.
 An obvious sufficient condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 to be consistent is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}^{-1}E[l(X_{ij},X_{ik})M_{ij}M_{ik}]=E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}^{-1}\pi_{k}^{-1}E[l(X_{ij},X_{i'k})M_{ij}M_{i'k}]=E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})]$
\end_inset

,
 and these conditions hold when the data is missing completely at random.
 We also require that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{X}>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}$
\end_inset

 to be defined,
 and that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}>0$
\end_inset

,
 so all rater combinations are counted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:hajek estimator"

\end_inset

The estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 are strongly consistent for all 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\{C,F,BP\}$
\end_inset

 when the data is missing completely at random,
 exchangeable raters or not,
 provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{X}>0$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
That 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}^{-1}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})M_{ij}M_{ik}]=E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})]$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})]=E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})|M_{ij}M_{ik}=1]$
\end_inset

,
 which holds true when data is missing completely at random.
 The same reasoning holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}^{-1}\pi_{k}^{-1}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})M_{ij}M_{i'k}]=E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})]$
\end_inset

 as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Motivation sketch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:hajek estimator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 is strongly consistent.
 This is nice,
 but we usually desire our estimators to be efficient.
 It is well-known form semi-parametric efficiency theory that this estimator is not efficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsiatis2006-sx"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Constructing efficient estimators either require complex semi-parametric machinery for general data or iterative methods such as the EM-algorithm for categorical data.
 We intend to explore the EM-algorithm in a future paper,
 but will remark that semiparametric methods for efficiency gains is likely to backfire,
 and the complexity is not worth the investment in our situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our motivation for the Hájek-type estimator cannot be based on efficiency directly,
 but we can make a weaker case for it.
 If we construct the population values 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 using the limits in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_IPW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the plugin-estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 is trivially efficient from standard theory.
 Moreover,
 it is consistent under reasonable assumptions that are weaker than missing completely at random.
 This is more than what we can say of its competitors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
On inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 are asymptotically normal under the mild condition that the random values 
\begin_inset Formula $l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})M_{ij}M_{ik}\hat{\pi}_{jk}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 have finite second moments.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\{C,F,BP\}$
\end_inset

,
 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{n}\big(\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}-\kappa_{X}^{IPW}\big)\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\sigma_{X}^{2}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

 is the almost sure limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{X}^{IPW}$
\end_inset

,
 which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}$
\end_inset

 under the conditions of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:hajek estimator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The complex formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which depends on unknown parameters,
 can be found using he efficient influence function in the observed-data model.
 We estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using a plug-in estimator of its influence functions.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{\kappa_{X}}=-d_{X}^{-1}\phi_{d}+d_{X}^{-2}\phi_{d_{X}}.\label{eq:influence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{jk}(x)=E[l(x,X_{1k})|M_{1k}=1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{jk}=\pi_{j}^{-1}\pi_{k}^{-1}E[l(X_{1j},X_{2k})M_{1j}M_{2k}]$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\theta_{jk}}=\pi_{j}^{-1}M_{j}(l_{k}(X_{1j})-\theta_{jk})+\pi_{k}^{-1}M_{j}(l_{k}(X_{1k})-\theta_{jk})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

